The paper presents a fully dynamic algorithm for the recognition of proper circular-arc graphs, which involves operations on the graph such as insertion and removal of vertices and edges. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves computational geometry techniques such as circular-arc representations, which suggests that it could also belong to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The paper also involves graph theory concepts such as connectivity and co-connectivity, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves the application of the algorithm to finding a minimal forbidden induced subgraph of a static graph, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category.
